<div id="review_3237637838" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3237637838" />
    <a title="Sleepless Dreamer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7614560-sleepless-dreamer"><img alt="Sleepless Dreamer" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1431177042p2/7614560.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3237637838?book_show_action=true">Mar 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sleepless Dreamer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sleepless Dreamer" href="/user/show/7614560-sleepless-dreamer">Sleepless Dreamer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780670023325" href="/book/show/11797365-escape-from-camp-14">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3237637838" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer396247351641714773">Long story short, does anyone want to recommend me positive and happy books because wow, this book was not happy at all. <br/><br/>This book tells the story of Shin, the only known defector who was born into a labor camp and managed to escape. This book is pretty short but it&apos;s an incredibly hard book to read. A lot of very terrible things happen. Harden&apos;s writing style is very matter of fact which only makes it more challenging to read as he simply describes these horrible situations. <br/><br/>And I can&apos;t stop th</span>
  <span id="freeText396247351641714773" style="display:none">Long story short, does anyone want to recommend me positive and happy books because wow, this book was not happy at all. <br /><br />This book tells the story of Shin, the only known defector who was born into a labor camp and managed to escape. This book is pretty short but it's an incredibly hard book to read. A lot of very terrible things happen. Harden's writing style is very matter of fact which only makes it more challenging to read as he simply describes these horrible situations. <br /><br />And I can't stop thinking about North Korea. The idea that people's darkest sides show up once they have nothing, the amount of terrible people that Shin encountered, the things that Shin himself did, it's all so overwhelming to think about. And sure, there are a few lighter moments but even then, they are smothered by fears that they aren't genuine. Like the teacher who was kind to Shin and in response, Shin wondered what he's getting out of it. <br /><br />Shin's story actually gets more and more interesting nowadays. Shin has apparently claimed that parts of his story are not real. For example, he says that he had already escaped to China before so he was not this clueless about life outside. Of course, it's impossible to verify anything as he is the only witness of it all. <br /><br />Beyond this, North Korea shared videos of his father claiming that he was in prison for raping a 13 year old girl. This prompting Shin to change other parts of his story as well but really, I found that the most telling part about this is that North Korea really cares. They care enough to post a video. Regardless of what's true in Shin's story, it makes you feel like there's much power in simply the awareness. <br /><br />I think I have a healthy amount of skepticism towards international activism. I've experienced so many Europeans and Americans lecture me about my own country and ugh, sure, tell me I'm a murderer for joining a mandatory army when you've never experienced any form of terror. It's hard to take seriously when I feel such activists work harder on making themselves feel ethical than actually improving the local population's life. <br /><br />Reading this book made me think that perhaps the true power of activism comes in the form of simply letting voices be heard. By translating Shin's story to English, it begins to have an impact that Shin alone couldn't have had. The organizations that Shin took part in seem to just focus on helping North Korean defectors, on making sure they can lead this battle. <br /><br />And as a person reading this, it's impossible not to feel angry and upset. Even if parts of Shin's story are fake, there's so much here that just seems wrong. It makes you ask what can you do to make it better (yes, I did find myself looking up universities in Seoul that offer my degree and internships that work with North Koreans, despite having about zero useful skills for such work). There's this immense sense of helplessness once you realize that there isn't a single country in the region that has an active desire to make the lives of North Koreans better. <br /><br />I found the parts that talked about how hard it is for North Koreans to blend into South Korea absolutely fascinating. Harden goes in depth about the policies that South Korea has to try and help them fit in and how the differences between the countries make it so hard to do so. The capitalism and competitive nature of South Korea is so different from North Korea who doesn't really push people to have ambition or personal responsibility. To think that Korea used to be one country but now, each part has split into such an opposite direction that they're just not the same anymore. <br /><br />When I finished the book, I opened up Google Maps and it's true, as the author says, the differences between the North and the South can be seen through satellites. You can see the wealth of Seoul just as easily as you can zoom into random North Korean cities and see the communist style buildings and the uniformity of it all. <br /><br />I found the parts about reunification interesting. South Koreans have this volatile border and experience occasional threats and attacks. Despite this, according to this book, South Koreans just don't seem to care much. Like, they are fond of the idea of reunification but don't want it to happen in their lifetimes because of the economic strain. They seem to just shrug all of this off. <br /><br />This book talks a bit about the way information is seeping into North Korea. Films, tv shows and radio shows are making their way in and hopefully, this will lead to North Koreans realizing the lies that they've been told and yet, it seems that years go by and North Korea is still managing to do its own thing. It's wild to think that in our generation, North Korea exists. This is very much in the present. <br /><br />I don't want to bring up the Holocaust, like I've seen many people do because it seems that the differences between the concentration camps there and in North Korea are very crucial. However, I do want to say that what I found horrifying was the snitching culture. When you read about Holocaust survivors, a lot of them survived because of comradery. Truly, Harden brings this up when he talks about Park. It really is awful to consider the sheer loneliness that such a culture promotes. <br /><br />I could probably go on because this book gave me much to think about but I also absolutely want to go over the essay I have to hand in before midnight so I will wrap this up now. If you're interested to learn about North Korea, I think <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40604846.Nothing_to_Envy_Ordinary_Lives_in_North_Korea" title="Nothing to Envy Ordinary Lives in North Korea by Barbara Demick" rel="nofollow noopener">Nothing to Envy: Ordinary Lives in North Korea</a> is a better book to start with because it's more general. However, if you'd like to learn more about the specific crimes of North Korea, this book definitely illustrates that. <br /><br /><b> What I'm Taking With Me </b> <br />- Passover is coming up and one of the things I adore about contemporary Judaism is the ability to discuss issues. I can't help but think of the way Shin's story will echo through the story about seeking justice. <br />- Can we also just congratulate Harden for managing to not be judgmental towards Shin, despite how tempting it is? Also, I loved that he mentioned his sources so clearly. I wish people in the academia did this because it really helps afterwards figuring out how to continue learning. <br />- Does anyone else also just feel <i>curious</i>? Like, I just want to know how it ends, I want to know what North Korea will look like in 200 years. <br /><br /><i> Quarantine Adventures</i><br />- The semester officially starts tomorrow and damn, I am not ready at all, I started reading my macro econ textbook and I just want to cry already. <br /><br />- However, I'm super excited to learn about the current global economic crisis, like all this time people have been telling us that we picked the right time to study Politics and well, now finally people are saying that it's the right time for Economics (unfortunately).<br /><br />- And I'm just really motivated. Like, yes, this semester is going to be so much better and I am going to get my life together finally. <br /><br />- Also, I have my first elective, which is a course about the European identity and identity politics in Europe and damn, I am so excited! I spent so much time in that seminar in Berlin talking about this with Germans so I'm stoked to hear an academic perspective.<br /><br />- And not that it matters this much, it's my first course that's taught by a woman. One of my classmates figured out that it's possible to complete a degree in PPE without being taught by a single woman so I'm glad that at least that won't happen to me (although, I have 8 courses and 7 are taught by men so things are quite terrible). <br /><br />- Imagine if this crisis lasts for longer than two months, I can't imagine not going outside in the summer, I'm literally someone who hibernates during the winter in order to spend tons of time outside in the summer. <br /><br />- However, it turns out my family is really great, who knew? <br /><br />- Ahhh, my essay awaits. It's weird because it's a very Econ based essay and I literally do not feel like I can talk about Econ without sounding like a child who's using big words they heard grownups say so like, here's hoping I managed to make enough sense, despite this. <br /><br />- I also feel like I cheated the word limit because I decided to call revealed preference theory RPT to cut the words I use and knowing my TA, this will make him laugh. I only hope it won't afterwards annoy him. Although come on, the word limit was 1500 words and I am pleased to say that I wrote exactly 1499 so the situation was very precarious. </span>
  <a data-text-id="396247351641714773" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
